<p class="EnTeteTranscription">Henry, Alexander. Travels in the Red River Department (Abridged), 1806. An electronic transcription. MFTP #0024</p><div class="ContenuPage">
<p style="text-align:justify;"><span class="fw">14</span>
</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;"><span class="fw">1806</span>
</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">July</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">When we informed them that we did not come on business but for pleasure and to see them and their Country &#8212; They could not comprehend why we should come so far merely through curiosity and became in consequence suspicious and would not beleive but we had goods which we kept for the indians of the other Villages.  This they were anxious to prevent and consequently teazed us till it was dark when they went away for the night much disappointed.  The young men now brought our horses and placed them in the same hut with Ourselves, which was a Spacious enclosure these people occupy on<span class="AddHand-author">e</span> side of their huts their horses the other this is done to guard them from thieves.  In the Evening taking a walk we observed both men and women going to the River to wash themselves.  In this operation the men make use of Clay to clear away the white and red paints with which they had dawbed themselves in the morning<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  The women wear a sort of leather shift.  This they slip off at some distance and wal<span class="AddHand-author">k</span> in the presence of the men as uncorzzedly as if they were alone.  Some of them make a slight covering with one hand but not through modesty for they at times go entirely</p>
<p style="text-align:right;"><span class="DelHand-author">naked</span> exposed</p>

<p align="page-number"><span class="AddHand-editors">[18]</span></p>

